{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01HMRd5T41PHYjD3PRWiG7nt","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me think about what drives aspect ratio. The aspect ratio is the ratio of the largest to smallest position variance. Gravity compresses Y variance, which helps if X or Z is bigger. But too much gravity makes the flock too flat and loses the elongated shape.\n\nThe roost attractor orbits in X-Z plane. If the Y amplitude is small (0.15) compared to X/Z (0.4), the flock gets pulled into a more pancake shape. \n\nWhat if I try reducing the sphereRadius? That constrains the flock into a smaller space. Or increasing the roost orbit speed to create more dynamics?\n\n\nActually, looking at the scoring formula, aspect ratio is capped at 5.0 and dynamics measures how much the shape changes between snapshots 100 frames apart. So I need the flock actively shifting its form. Increasing the roost orbit speed should push the flock to follow a faster-moving attractor, creating more shape variation and potentially more elongation as it stretches to keep up.\n\nI'll bump the roost speed from 0.002 to 0.004 and see if that drives more dynamic behavior.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":733,"cache_read_input_tokens":60725,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":733},"output_tokens":10,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0d6d1a49-a9d2-43e7-86d8-3b4d26279dc9","uuid":"6651ca8f-e170-49eb-8aec-0017e7d10dde"}
