{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01525MMNyfydHEAhybN3QvJi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me think differently. The baseline already had aspect ratio of 3.60 and gravity of 0.03. Gravity 0.06 improved to 3.95 (kept). \n\nThe aspect ratio measures largest/smallest position variance. If the flock is stretched into a long thin band (not just flat), that gives a better aspect ratio.\n\nWhat if I reduce the roost Y amplitude to make the roost move more in a flat plane? Currently roost Y = cos(time * 0.7) * sphere_radius * 0.15. If I reduce this to 0.05, the roost stays flatter, and gravity pulls the flock flatter.\n\n\nI could increase the sphere radius to let the flock spread more, but the preset is already locked at 120. Instead, I'll reduce the roost Y amplitude from 0.15 to 0.05 — this keeps the attractor moving in a flatter orbit, which combined with gravity should stretch the flock more along the X/Z plane and improve the aspect ratio.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":609,"cache_read_input_tokens":62429,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":609},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0d6d1a49-a9d2-43e7-86d8-3b4d26279dc9","uuid":"0fd0c471-a5da-4a41-a048-1954566c407b"}
